{
  "texts": [
    "Later, PolyU announced that it takes an \"open and forward-looking stance\" on the use of GenAI and published the \"Guidelines for Students on the Use of Generative Artificial Intelligence\".",
    "5Both guidelines from PolyU and CUHK make it clear that, by default, the universities prohibit the use of any AI tools for assignments that contribute to students' grades.",
    "Any student who breaks this rule will be perceived as committing academic dishonesty and will face disciplinary action; unless the use of AI tools is specifically approved in the course outlines and/or assignment instructions, which students should take responsibility to check and seek clarification from course coordinators if in doubt.",
    "However, unlike the guideline released by CUHK (focused on the Dont's), PolyU is more on advising students on how to properly use generative AI tools, how to declare the use of AI tools in the assignments, and how to reference AI-generated materials in different formats (focused on the Do's).",
    "PoluU's guideline is from a more educational perspective instead of a disciplinary perspective.On the first of June, HKUST launched its only version of ChatGPT for both teachers and students for one year, with each person having a monthly usage limit of a maximum of 20 \"prompts\" during each chat."
  ]
}